00:48:21.290 --> 00:48:23.500
So we discussed that.

00:48:23.500 --> 00:48:28.170
And I think that for me the
way to not be as anxious--

00:48:28.170 --> 00:48:30.660
because like when I was going
to jump into 32 degree water

00:48:30.660 --> 00:48:34.160
off Antarctica there was a
moment I'm walking down the

00:48:34.160 --> 00:48:35.900
steps and they feel like
ice cube trays.

00:48:35.900 --> 00:48:38.680
And then I'm sitting on
it, waiting to sort of

00:48:38.680 --> 00:48:40.380
slide into the water.

00:48:40.380 --> 00:48:45.136
And I'm thinking, wow, this is
going to be really difficult,

00:48:45.136 --> 00:48:48.410
and it's going to be cold,
and am I going to be OK?

00:48:48.410 --> 00:48:52.880
So I go back to I
train for it.

00:48:52.880 --> 00:48:55.360
I'm prepared for it.

00:48:55.360 --> 00:48:57.980
I've done what I needed to do
and now this is the moment I

00:48:57.980 --> 00:48:59.130
get to do it.

00:48:59.130 --> 00:49:02.860
And that's really a great way
to start off, like finally I

00:49:02.860 --> 00:49:04.410
get to do it.

00:49:04.410 --> 00:49:06.250
Instead of like, oh, my gosh,
what's going to go wrong?

00:49:06.250 --> 00:49:07.830
It's like what's going
to go right?

00:49:07.830 --> 00:49:10.990
And all the stuff I've learned
through all this time, how can

00:49:10.990 --> 00:49:12.960
I now apply it for
this moment?

00:49:12.960 --> 00:49:16.170
Because no matter how hard you
train, there will be stuff

00:49:16.170 --> 00:49:18.160
that comes up and it will
be something new.

00:49:18.160 --> 00:49:20.850
It was so cool, the last of
couple years I got a chance to

00:49:20.850 --> 00:49:23.030
work with the SEALs,
Navy SEALs.

00:49:23.030 --> 00:49:25.300
And what I learned from them
was that they prepare, and

00:49:25.300 --> 00:49:26.940
prepare, and train, and train,
and train, and train.

00:49:26.940 --> 00:49:30.590
And they do things so that it
becomes part of muscle memory.

00:49:30.590 --> 00:49:33.400
And so that when something weird
happens, they've already

00:49:33.400 --> 00:49:35.690
covered all those other bases
and then they can deal with

00:49:35.690 --> 00:49:36.860
whatever is new.

00:49:36.860 --> 00:49:39.730
And I thought that was so
helpful to be able to have

00:49:39.730 --> 00:49:42.560
that mindset of you've done
everything you can.

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:45.130
But now, you're the athlete and
you can find the balance

00:49:45.130 --> 00:49:47.770
you need to do what you need to
do and shift the thinking

00:49:47.770 --> 00:49:53.900
from oh, my god, now what,
to oh, I get to go now.

00:49:53.900 --> 00:49:55.460
I hope that helps.

00:49:58.290 --> 00:50:00.110
AUDIENCE: Did you
ever flatline?

00:50:00.110 --> 00:50:00.860
LYNNE COX: Did I ever flatline,

00:50:00.860 --> 00:50:01.530
what a great question?

00:50:01.530 --> 00:50:04.310
Yeah, actually I-- ugh.

00:50:04.310 --> 00:50:04.760
OK.

00:50:04.760 --> 00:50:08.550
I once was invited to swim
in a race in Nile River.

00:50:08.550 --> 00:50:10.010
And we were supposed
to swim around two

00:50:10.010 --> 00:50:11.830
islands in the Nile.

00:50:11.830 --> 00:50:14.900
And one of my mentors was a man
named Fami Attala, who had

00:50:14.900 --> 00:50:17.420
attempted the English Channel
five times and never made it.

00:50:17.420 --> 00:50:20.220
But he had done an 80-mile swim
in the Mediterranean.

00:50:20.220 --> 00:50:21.120
He grew up in Egypt.

00:50:21.120 --> 00:50:24.080
And he told me that you'll
have like the best swim.

00:50:24.080 --> 00:50:24.890
It'll be the best thing.

00:50:24.890 --> 00:50:25.890
It'll be the best experience.

00:50:25.890 --> 00:50:29.690
Because in Egypt, open water
swimming there is such a big

00:50:29.690 --> 00:50:32.530
thing that they name streets
after their heroes.

00:50:32.530 --> 00:50:34.530
Abouheif was one of their
swimmers that

00:50:34.530 --> 00:50:35.220
swam the English Channel.

00:50:35.220 --> 00:50:38.060
So he has a street named
after him in Cairo.

00:50:38.060 --> 00:50:40.850
And it's part of their
mythology.

00:50:40.850 --> 00:50:43.580
It's bigger than being
an NFL quarterback is

00:50:43.580 --> 00:50:44.920
in the United States.

00:50:44.920 --> 00:50:50.510
So Fami got me all excited and
set up to do the swim.

00:50:50.510 --> 00:50:55.150
And I got dysentery the week
before I swam, but decided I

00:50:55.150 --> 00:50:56.880
was the only American there

00:50:56.880 --> 00:50:58.010
representing the United States.

00:50:58.010 --> 00:50:59.830
So I had to do my best.

00:50:59.830 --> 00:51:03.700
So I jumped into the water and
swam 15 of the 20 miles and

00:51:03.700 --> 00:51:06.300
pretty much passed
out in the water.

00:51:06.300 --> 00:51:10.820
And wound up in the ER room
in Egypt, in Cairo, Egypt.

00:51:10.820 --> 00:51:14.140
Which was really kind of
fortunate because the doctor

00:51:14.140 --> 00:51:17.060
who was attending to me had
studied in Britain and spoke

00:51:17.060 --> 00:51:18.600
English fluently.

00:51:18.600 --> 00:51:22.090
And I was so upset because
I had failed.

00:51:22.090 --> 00:51:24.680
I mean I had really failed.

00:51:24.680 --> 00:51:27.370
And he couldn't understand
why I was so upset.

00:51:27.370 --> 00:51:30.035
And I kept saying well, but I
didn't complete the swim.

00:51:30.035 --> 00:51:32.100
And he saying, but
you don't get it.

00:51:32.100 --> 00:51:32.880
You could have died.

00:51:32.880 --> 00:51:35.760
You were severely dehydrated.

00:51:35.760 --> 00:51:37.280
Your muscles were cramping.

00:51:37.280 --> 00:51:39.650
And you could have died.

00:51:39.650 --> 00:51:42.550
Like, yeah, but I didn't
finish the swim.

00:51:42.550 --> 00:51:44.130
I mean I was 17 years old.

00:51:44.130 --> 00:51:45.000
I'm like aah.

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:49.460
And so it took me years
to figure out oh, I

00:51:49.460 --> 00:51:50.980
pushed it too far.

00:51:50.980 --> 00:51:52.800
I was really dehydrated.

00:51:52.800 --> 00:51:54.450
I really could have died.

00:51:54.450 --> 00:51:57.430
And no swim is ever
worth that.

00:51:57.430 --> 00:52:01.240
So it put everything from
then on in perspective.

00:52:01.240 --> 00:52:04.850
But for a while, that
failure haunted me.

00:52:04.850 --> 00:52:08.910
Because with the Cook Strait
swim that came after that, I

00:52:08.910 --> 00:52:11.730
almost quit on that swim after
swimming for five hours and

00:52:11.730 --> 00:52:12.910
not getting anywhere.

00:52:12.910 --> 00:52:16.160
But then the support
crew continued to

00:52:16.160 --> 00:52:16.920
say you can do it.

00:52:16.920 --> 00:52:17.490
You can keep going.

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:20.200
And so I just thought OK,
I can keep going.

00:52:20.200 --> 00:52:21.850
So 12 hours later, I made it.

00:52:21.850 --> 00:52:25.730
But that swim in the Nile
was really awful.

00:52:25.730 --> 00:52:27.350
Because it was also extremely
polluted.

00:52:27.350 --> 00:52:30.990
And I was swimming through areas
of dead rats that were

00:52:30.990 --> 00:52:32.990
floating around and dead dogs.

00:52:32.990 --> 00:52:35.710
And it was really bad.

00:52:35.710 --> 00:52:36.255
Yeah.

00:52:36.255 --> 00:52:37.290
I wouldn't recommend it.

00:52:37.290 --> 00:52:39.990
Don't swim in the Nile?

00:52:39.990 --> 00:52:41.840
A happier question?

00:52:41.840 --> 00:52:42.990
AUDIENCE: I was curious.

00:52:42.990 --> 00:52:45.680
Whenever I hit a certain
mileage,

00:52:45.680 --> 00:52:46.970
my foot always cramps.

00:52:46.970 --> 00:52:50.720
So what do you do?

00:52:50.720 --> 00:52:52.670
What do you do when
you have cramps?

00:52:52.670 --> 00:52:54.400
LYNNE COX: Actually,
I just grab my foot

00:52:54.400 --> 00:52:55.610
and stretch it out.

00:52:55.610 --> 00:52:59.370
And that helps to
ease the cramp.

00:52:59.370 --> 00:53:01.680
AUDIENCE: So are you always
just treading water?

00:53:01.680 --> 00:53:02.403
You have your support crew.

00:53:02.403 --> 00:53:03.670
Do you hold onto your--

00:53:03.670 --> 00:53:04.580
LYNNE COX: You never
hold onto the boat.

00:53:04.580 --> 00:53:07.880
But I don't know if this is in
training or if this is during

00:53:07.880 --> 00:53:08.740
an actual race.

00:53:08.740 --> 00:53:11.280
If it's during training, I would
just hold on to whatever

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:12.390
and do that.

00:53:12.390 --> 00:53:15.780
But usually what happens with
cramps is that somebody has

00:53:15.780 --> 00:53:19.620
either their electrolytes are
out of balance and so maybe

00:53:19.620 --> 00:53:22.820
you're aren't having enough
calcium, or sodium chloride,

00:53:22.820 --> 00:53:23.570
or anything.

00:53:23.570 --> 00:53:27.180
Maybe you need to talk to your
doctor or whatever and find

00:53:27.180 --> 00:53:30.700
out if you should have
something more, more

00:53:30.700 --> 00:53:32.540
electrolyte replacement.

00:53:32.540 --> 00:53:35.260
The other thing that happens
though is your muscles fatigue

00:53:35.260 --> 00:53:36.460
at a certain point.

00:53:36.460 --> 00:53:40.230
And so maybe you're not training
hard enough, those

00:53:40.230 --> 00:53:43.360
muscles in your feet, to prepare
you for the swim.

00:53:43.360 --> 00:53:45.990
Maybe they're fatiguing and
that's causing the cramping.

00:53:45.990 --> 00:53:49.830
Or the other thing is you
may be kicking too hard.

00:53:49.830 --> 00:53:53.830
A lot of swimmers don't realize
that 80% of their

00:53:53.830 --> 00:53:55.380
propulsion comes from
their arms.

00:53:55.380 --> 00:53:58.000
And their legs are
more for balance.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:00.330
And so if you're kicking really
hard, you're using all

00:54:00.330 --> 00:54:01.960
the energy that could
be pulling you

00:54:01.960 --> 00:54:03.390
forward with your arms.

00:54:03.390 --> 00:54:06.560
So if you look at me swim, and I
did the long distance stuff,

00:54:06.560 --> 00:54:08.710
you'll see my stoke
is really arms.

00:54:08.710 --> 00:54:10.420
And my legs are just balance.

00:54:10.420 --> 00:54:13.200
So you might try backing off
on you kick a little bit.

00:54:13.200 --> 00:54:15.850
So then you can use your oxygen
for your arms and pull

00:54:15.850 --> 00:54:17.580
more strongly with your
arms and see if that

00:54:17.580 --> 00:54:19.240
increases your speed.

00:54:19.240 --> 00:54:22.100
And then you don't get the
cramps in your feet.

00:54:22.100 --> 00:54:26.160
You know, like a variety of
things you might try.

00:54:26.160 --> 00:54:26.980
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:54:26.980 --> 00:54:28.010
LYNNE COX: Oh, sure.

00:54:28.010 --> 00:54:30.610
AUDIENCE: So swimming for such
a long distance, how do you

00:54:30.610 --> 00:54:31.860
keep straight?

00:54:34.240 --> 00:54:35.826
LYNNE COX: When I'm swimming for
such a long distance, how

00:54:35.826 --> 00:54:36.740
do I keep straight?

00:54:36.740 --> 00:54:39.810
I always have boats with me that
are supporting me during

00:54:39.810 --> 00:54:41.260
the actual swim.

00:54:41.260 --> 00:54:44.280
So on board the boat will
be usually a doctor.

00:54:44.280 --> 00:54:47.160
And there will be lifeguards
and sometimes a paramedic.

00:54:47.160 --> 00:54:50.290
But on the big, really cold
swims, I've actually had three

00:54:50.290 --> 00:54:52.900
doctors there just in case
something goes wrong.

00:54:52.900 --> 00:54:55.740
Because again, I'm going to
places nobody's been and I've

00:54:55.740 --> 00:54:56.300
never been.

00:54:56.300 --> 00:54:59.100
So I want to make sure
there's back up.

00:54:59.100 --> 00:55:01.630
And they also go through this
rehearsal ahead of the swim to

00:55:01.630 --> 00:55:03.750
make sure they can
take care of me.

00:55:03.750 --> 00:55:07.060
When I'm training offshore,
I swim just

00:55:07.060 --> 00:55:08.800
outside the wave break.

00:55:08.800 --> 00:55:13.200
And I swim usually in an area,
either it's roped off, so I

00:55:13.200 --> 00:55:17.270
know I can follow the
rope along the way.

00:55:17.270 --> 00:55:18.930
Or I swim outside
the wave break.

00:55:18.930 --> 00:55:22.810
And there's a pier in Seal Beach
where put-- there's a

00:55:22.810 --> 00:55:25.150
tower and I put it on my back.

00:55:25.150 --> 00:55:28.440
And then in the distance, there
are three Oil Islands,

00:55:28.440 --> 00:55:30.530
White, Chaffee, and Grissom,
that were named after the

00:55:30.530 --> 00:55:34.560
Apollo 11 astronauts that were
killed in the Apollo mission.

00:55:34.560 --> 00:55:36.550
And they have lights on them.

00:55:36.550 --> 00:55:39.500
So if it's late afternoon or
early evening, I can use those

00:55:39.500 --> 00:55:40.670
lights as my guide.

00:55:40.670 --> 00:55:42.750
So I'll swim along
and I'll look up.

00:55:42.750 --> 00:55:46.200
But the other thing that I do
that really helps you swim in

00:55:46.200 --> 00:55:49.090
the open water is to be able
to breathe on both sides.

00:55:49.090 --> 00:55:51.480
Because if you can breathe on
both sides, then you can see

00:55:51.480 --> 00:55:52.420
on both sides.

00:55:52.420 --> 00:55:55.170
And you can swim in a
more balanced way.

00:55:55.170 --> 00:55:59.710
But you also can see what's
around you for safety.

00:55:59.710 --> 00:56:03.460
And so there might be a jet
skier coming off this side.

00:56:03.460 --> 00:56:04.820
And if you don't breathe
on that side, you

00:56:04.820 --> 00:56:05.530
might not see him.

00:56:05.530 --> 00:56:08.280
Or a wind surfer on this side--
and if you only breath

00:56:08.280 --> 00:56:10.110
on this side, then you won't
see the wind surfer and you

00:56:10.110 --> 00:56:11.340
might not hear him.

00:56:11.340 --> 00:56:14.520
So it's just really important
to be able to see, and look,

00:56:14.520 --> 00:56:15.900
and use your eyes.

00:56:15.900 --> 00:56:19.690
That will help your
body balance.

00:56:19.690 --> 00:56:21.150
AUDIENCE: And a quick
question.

00:56:21.150 --> 00:56:25.340
Did you wear the thermal suit
or the normal bathing suit?

00:56:25.340 --> 00:56:26.710
LYNNE COX: Normal
bathing suit.

00:56:26.710 --> 00:56:28.880
Usually it's a TYR
bathing suit.

00:56:28.880 --> 00:56:32.970
It's just a Lycra swimsuit,
like the Lycra shorts that

00:56:32.970 --> 00:56:33.710
cyclists wear.

00:56:33.710 --> 00:56:36.600
So I'll wear the Lycra swimsuit
because it doesn't

00:56:36.600 --> 00:56:37.200
chafe as much.

00:56:37.200 --> 00:56:40.380
If you wear a nylon or a
polyester swim suit, that, if

00:56:40.380 --> 00:56:42.900
you're swimming a long way, even
if it's a short way, it

00:56:42.900 --> 00:56:44.340
can start chaffing.

00:56:44.340 --> 00:56:45.700
So I wrote all about that.

00:56:45.700 --> 00:56:51.440
So it's all in there about
how to prepare.

00:56:51.440 --> 00:56:51.670
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:56:51.670 --> 00:56:52.920
LYNNE COX: Thank
you very much.

00:56:55.352 --> 00:56:56.630
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's
all we have time for.

00:56:56.630 --> 00:56:58.330
Thank you for joining
us today.

00:56:58.330 --> 00:56:58.980
LYNNE COX: Thank
you very much.

00:56:58.980 --> 00:56:59.750
It was great.

00:56:59.750 --> 00:57:00.100
Thank you.

00:57:00.100 --> 00:57:01.350
Thank you.

